Is it allowed to share API keys?

I assume not.

I would like to put the API key here so 
that the script can load it into the 
environment to install and configure 
wtt, so that manual installation is not 
needed.

To implement that I would need to, and 
I see a reason not to, include API keys
in the repository.

I am not doing that, but the question 
is still open.

If GitHub tries to prevent someone to 
include API keys in the repository, 
I consider that to be an example of 
a bad API.

API keys are there to provide function
in an application and in the public 
domain APIs their use should not violate 
common sense.

I use API keys of Google and GitHub and 
I think that they are wrong. 

If they think that it is wrong for me to 
publish the gemini API key on GitHub 
for example, then they would also be 
against using cat on the key.

```sh
cat api-key
```
.

It is interesting.

Suppose it is not allowed to share api-keys.
I can still make the script work, if the 
user stores their wtt key, or google gemini key
as a file in
```sh
~/.api-keys/gemini
```
api-keys directory.

Let us do that.
